SIMPLE: list
RECORDS: 10

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: List
<hw>List</hw> <pr>(l⟦icr⟧st)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>lice</ets>, LL. <ets>liciae</ets>, pl., from L. <ets>licium</ets>
thread, girdle.]</ety> <def>A line inclosing or forming the extremity of
a piece of ground, or field of combat; hence, in the plural
(<xex>lists</xex>), the ground or field inclosed for a race or
combat.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In measured <qex>lists</qex> to toss the weighty lance.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To enter the lists</b></col>, <cd>to accept a challenge,
or engage in contest.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>List</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: List
<hw>List</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To inclose for combat; <as>as, to
<ex>list</ex> a field</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>List</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: List
<hw>List</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Listen</er>.]</ety>
<def>To hearken; to attend; to listen.</def> <mark>[Obs. <plain>except
in poetry</plain>.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Stand close, and <qex>list</qex> to him.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>List</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: List
<hw>List</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To listen or hearken to.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then weigh what loss your honor may sustain,⟦br⟧
If with too credent ear you <qex>list</qex> his songs.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>List</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: List
<hw>List</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>listen</ets>,
<ets>lusten</ets>, AS. <ets>lystan</ets>, from <ets>lust</ets> pleasure.
See <er>Lust</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To desire or choose; to
please.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The wind bloweth where it <qex>listeth</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>John
iii. 8.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Them that add to the Word of God what them <qex>listeth</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let other men think of your devices as they <qex>list</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Whitgift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To lean; to incline; <as>as, the
ship <ex>lists</ex> to port</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>List</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: List
<hw>List</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Inclination; desire.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>An inclination to one side;
<as>as, the ship has a <ex>list</ex> to starboard</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>List</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 7 ====
HEADWORD: List
<hw>List</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>l⟦imac⟧st</ets> a list of
cloth; akin to D. <ets>lijst</ets>, G. <ets>leiste</ets>, OHG.
<ets>l⟦imac⟧sta</ets>, Icel. <ets>lista</ets>, <ets>listi</ets>, Sw.
<ets>list</ets>, Dan. <ets>liste</ets>. In sense 5 from F.
<ets>liste</ets>, of German origin, and thus ultimately the same
word.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A strip forming the woven border or
selvedge of cloth, particularly of broadcloth, and serving to strengthen
it; hence, a strip of cloth; a fillet.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Gartered with a red
and blue <xex>list</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 859 --></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A limit or boundary; a border.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The very <qex>list</qex>, the very utmost bound,⟦br⟧
Of all our fortunes.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The lobe of the ear; the ear itself.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A stripe.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir T.
Browne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A roll or catalogue, that is, row or line; a record
of names; <as>as, a <ex>list</ex> of names, books, articles; a
<ex>list</ex> of ratable estate.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He was the ablest emperor of all the <qex>list</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A little square molding; a
fillet; -- called also <altname>listel</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Carp.)</fld> <def>A narrow strip of wood, esp.
sapwood, cut from the edge of a plank or board.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Rope Making)</fld> <def>A piece of woolen cloth
with which the yarns are grasped by a workman.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Tin-plate Manuf.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The first
thin coat of tin.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A wirelike rim of tin left on
an edge of the plate after it is coated.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Civil list</b></col> (<mark>Great Britain & U.S.</mark>),
<cd>the civil officers of government, as judges, ambassadors,
secretaries, etc. Hence, the revenues or appropriations of public money
for the support of the civil officers. More recently, the <xex>civil
list</xex>, in England, embraces only the expenses of the reigning
monarch's household.</cd> -- <col><b>Free list</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd>
<cd>A list of articles admitted to a country free of duty.</cd>
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A list of persons admitted to any entertainment, as a
theater or opera, without payment, or to whom a periodical, or the like,
is furnished without cost.</cd></cs></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Roll; catalogue; register; inventory;
schedule.</syn> <usage> -- <er>List</er>, <er>Roll</er>,
<er>Catalogue</er>, <er>Register</er>, <er>Inventory</er>,
<er>Schedule</er>. A <xex>list</xex> is properly a simple series of
names, etc., in a brief form, such as might naturally be entered in a
narrow strip of paper. A <xex>roll</xex> was originally a list
containing the names of persons belonging to a public body (as
Parliament, etc.), which was <xex>rolled</xex> up and laid aside among
its archives. A <xex>catalogue</xex> is a list of persons or things
arranged in order, and usually containing some description of the same,
more or less extended. A <xex>register</xex> is designed for record or
preservation. An <xex>inventory</xex> is a list of articles, found on
hand in a store of goods, or in the estate of a deceased person, or
under similar circumstances. A <xex>schedule</xex> is a formal list or
inventory prepared for legal or business purposes.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>List</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 8 ====
HEADWORD: List
<hw>List</hw> <pr>(l⟦icr⟧st)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Listed</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Listing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[From <ets>list</ets> a
roll.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To sew together, as strips of cloth, so as
to make a show of colors, or form a border.</def> <rj><au>Sir H.
Wotton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cover with list, or with strips of cloth; to put
list on; <as>as, to <ex>list</ex> a door</as>; to stripe as if with
list.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The tree that stood white-<qex>listed</qex> through the gloom.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To enroll; to place or register in a list.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Listed</qex> among the upper serving men.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To engage, as a soldier; to enlist.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will <qex>list</qex> you for my soldier.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Carp.)</fld> <def>To cut away a narrow strip, as of
sapwood, from the edge of; <as>as, to <ex>list</ex> a
board</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To list a stock</b></col> <fld>(Stock Exchange)</fld>,
<cd>to put it in the list of stocks called at the meeting of the
board.</cd></cs><-- to put it on a list of stocks which may be traded on
a specific stock exchange -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>List</ent>⟦br⟧

